title="Polynomials form a vector space">vector space of polynomials</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}[z]]]></fr:tex> is an infinite-dimensional vector space.</fr:p><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\subseteq \mathbb {F}[z]]]></fr:tex> be any finite set, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N=\{\deg (p)\mid  p\in  S\}]]></fr:tex>. Then consider the smallest positive integer <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> which is not <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\notin  N]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z^{n}\notin \mathrm {span}(S)]]></fr:tex>. So <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}[z]]]></fr:tex> cannot be finite-dimensional.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
