display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> be a real vector space.</fr:p><fr:p>If there is a finite basis <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex>, then we define the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Dimension</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> to be the number <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim (V)]]></fr:tex> of elements of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Otherwise, we define the dimension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> to be <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim (V)=\infty ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>When <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim (V)<\infty ]]></fr:tex>, we say <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Finite-Dimensional</html:dfn>. Otherwise <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Infinite-Dimensional</html:dfn>.</fr:p><fr:p>For example, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim (\mathbb {R}^{n})=n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim (\mathbb {R}[x])=\infty ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>